            <h2>Investment Thesis Summary</h2>
            <div class="assumptions-grid">
                <div class="assumption-card">
                    <h4>Bull Case</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>New EV launches regain share in premium/mid segments.</li>
                        <li>JLR margin expansion, CV leadership.</li>
                        <li>Policy support for Indian manufacturing/EV ecosystem.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="assumption-card">
                    <h4>Bear Case</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Further loss of EV market share (&lt;30% by mid-2026).</li>
                        <li>JLR/profit hit from global slowdown.</li>
                        <li>Margin compression from subsidy phase-out.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="assumption-card">
                    <h4>Strategic Allocation</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Aggressive: Up to 10%</li>
                        <li>Moderate: 5–7%</li>
                        <li>Conservative: Max 3–4%</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight">
                <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Tata Motors remains a central player in India’s EV transformation but faces intense competition. The ₹820 target reflects reasonable upside if new launches succeed, but execution risks are high.</p>
